Counting nodes and leaves.

Both operations follow the same combine-the-subtrees pattern.

To count all nodes, the total is one plus the count from the left subtree plus the count from the right subtree. To count only leaves, a node contributes one if it has no children and zero otherwise, with the results from the left and right subtrees added together.

This is the recursive skeleton you will see again and again with trees: solve the problem for the left subtree, solve it for the right subtree, and combine those two answers with whatever the current node contributes.
